Gravitational potential energy on surface on Earth is<br>\[
U_{E}=\frac{-G M m}{R}
\]<br>where \( M \) is mass of Earth; \( m \) is mass on surface of Earth; \( R \) is radius; \( G \) is gravitational constant<br>When mass \( m \) is shifted to a target then potential energy is<br>\[
U=\frac{-G M m}{(R+R)}=\frac{-G M m}{2 R}
\]<br>Work done in the process is<br>\[
\begin{array}{l}
W=U-U_{E}=-\frac{G M m}{2 R}-\left(-\frac{G M m}{R}\right)=-\frac{G M m}{2 R}+\frac{G M m}{R} \\
\Rightarrow W=\frac{G M m}{2 R}
\end{array}
\]<br>Now substitute \( G M=g R^{2} \), we get<br>\[
W=\frac{g R^{2} m}{2 R}=\frac{g R m}{2}
\]<br>Therefore, work done in process \( =\frac{m g R}{2} \)

